00:01:29,388 --> 00:01:31,189
Thank you for your help
last season,

30
00:01:31,190 --> 00:01:34,692
but I've got this new thing
I want to look into.

31
00:01:34,693 --> 00:01:36,327
I started thinking a lot
about belief

32
00:01:36,328 --> 00:01:37,762
and how we form them.

33
00:01:37,763 --> 00:01:42,534
Specifically beliefs about
what causes our behavior.

34
00:01:42,535 --> 00:01:44,702
I want to be able
to break it down

35
00:01:44,703 --> 00:01:47,205
and just look at how people
respond to the environment
around them

36
00:01:47,206 --> 00:01:48,840
and how it changes
their belief.

37
00:01:48,841 --> 00:01:51,709
Well, a Skinner Box
is a great place to start.

38
00:01:51,710 --> 00:01:54,212
because what
I tell my students is,

39
00:01:54,213 --> 00:01:57,215
a Skinner Box,
for a psychologist
like myself,

40
00:01:57,216 --> 00:01:59,417
is like a test tube
for a chemist.

41
00:01:59,418 --> 00:02:01,753
 Dr. Skinner, what are you
 doing with this pigeon?

42
00:02:01,754 --> 00:02:05,490
 I'm getting ready to
 demonstrate a fundamental
 principle of behavior.

43
00:02:05,491 --> 00:02:08,393
Michael:
 Invented by Harvard
 psychologist B.F. Skinner,

44
00:02:08,394 --> 00:02:11,196
 a Skinner Box is a chamber
 in which animals

45
00:02:11,197 --> 00:02:14,799
 can be isolated and exposed to
 carefully controlled stimuli.

46
00:02:14,800 --> 00:02:16,801
 In one of his
 landmark experiments,

47
00:02:16,802 --> 00:02:19,370
 Skinner released food
 to pigeons in the boxes

48
00:02:19,371 --> 00:02:20,972
 at regular intervals.

49
00:02:20,973 --> 00:02:22,874
 What he found was that
 the pigeons seemed to believe

50
00:02:22,875 --> 00:02:24,442
 that whatever
 they happened to be doing

51
00:02:24,443 --> 00:02:25,944
 just before the food came

52
00:02:25,945 --> 00:02:28,313
 actually caused the food
 to appear,

53
00:02:28,314 --> 00:02:30,548
 and would then repeat
 that behavior over and over--

54
00:02:30,549 --> 00:02:34,352
 for example, hopping around
 or spinning in circles.

55
00:02:34,353 --> 00:02:38,323
 Skinner called this
 "superstitious behavior."

56
00:02:38,324 --> 00:02:42,927
So what do you want to do--
what's your dream test?

57
00:02:42,928 --> 00:02:46,998
Basically a replication
of Skinner's superstitious
experiment,

58
00:02:46,999 --> 00:02:49,000
but instead of with pigeons,
with people.

59
00:02:49,001 --> 00:02:51,936
I would love to see:
will people develop

60
00:02:51,937 --> 00:02:55,707
their own sort of
superstitious rituals
or beliefs.

61
00:02:55,708 --> 00:02:57,942
Have we done this
with people before?

62
00:02:57,943 --> 00:03:01,779
I don't think
such a rigorous test
of this has been done.

63
00:03:01,780 --> 00:03:09,754
I think primarily, from
the literature I know,
it's pretty much pigeons.

64
00:03:09,755 --> 00:03:12,257
B.F. Skinner's work
showed that if you

65
00:03:12,258 --> 00:03:14,659
regularly deliver
a reward to a pigeon,

66
00:03:14,660 --> 00:03:16,628
regardless of how
it actually acts,

67
00:03:16,629 --> 00:03:18,596
the pigeon won't
figure that out.

68
00:03:18,597 --> 00:03:22,600
Instead, the pigeon will develop
superstitious behaviors

69
00:03:22,601 --> 00:03:24,936
as if it thinks
it is in control,

70
00:03:24,937 --> 00:03:27,338
despite the lack of
any evidence that it is.

71
00:03:27,339 --> 00:03:28,906
 But what about humans?

72
00:03:28,907 --> 00:03:31,442
 Watching people form
 new superstitions

73
00:03:31,443 --> 00:03:34,646
 might show us how
 beliefs are created,
 but here's the thing:

74
00:03:34,647 --> 00:03:37,448
You can't just put a person
in a Skinner Box.

75
00:03:37,449 --> 00:03:39,684
People are quite clever,
and so instead,

76
00:03:39,685 --> 00:03:41,519
along with Dr. Aaron Blaisdell,

77
00:03:41,520 --> 00:03:43,921
I have developed
a much more elaborate ruse.

78
00:03:43,922 --> 00:03:47,525
Welcome to Victory Vault.

79
00:03:47,526 --> 00:03:50,595
 â™ª

80
00:03:50,596 --> 00:03:54,032
Michael: "Victory Vault"
 is a fake game show we made up

81
00:03:54,033 --> 00:03:56,401
 to draw our
 unsuspecting subjects

82
00:03:56,402 --> 00:03:59,003
 into taking part in
 a human Skinner Box.

83
00:03:59,004 --> 00:04:01,773
 To accomplish this,
 we rented a sound stage

84
00:04:01,774 --> 00:04:04,709
 and constructed what appeared
 to be a game show set,

85
00:04:04,710 --> 00:04:06,511
 but was really our study.

86
00:04:06,512 --> 00:04:08,846
 We outfitted the room
 with a checkboard floor,

87
00:04:08,847 --> 00:04:11,049
 a button that serves
 no purpose,

88
00:04:11,050 --> 00:04:13,651
 multiple cameras
 and a live microphone,

89
00:04:13,652 --> 00:04:17,088
 all of which have absolutely no
 connection to winning the game.

90
00:04:17,089 --> 00:04:21,059
 We also included
 an ATM slot on the wall
 where, instead of food,

91
00:04:21,060 --> 00:04:23,661
 dollar bills would be fed
 into the room

92
00:04:23,662 --> 00:04:25,396
 at regular intervals.

93
00:04:25,397 --> 00:04:27,465
 Meanwhile, I would be
 playing the role

94
00:04:27,466 --> 00:04:29,834
 of the executive producer
 of this new game show

95
00:04:29,835 --> 00:04:32,537
 testing out the concept
 for a television network.

96
00:04:32,538 --> 00:04:34,906
 Our first subject is Rebecca.

97
00:04:34,907 --> 00:04:36,874
Yes, I know nothing.
I'm excited.

98
00:04:36,875 --> 00:04:38,676
Excellent, excellent.

99
00:04:38,677 --> 00:04:40,878
Well, I'll you some things
that you need to know.

100
